---
// src/pages/lab/pitch-1517.astro
import LabBase from '../../layouts/LabBase.astro';
---
<LabBase title="1517 Pitch" description="Polarity Lab — 1517 Fund pitch and meeting prep.">
  <div class="gate" id="gate">
    <form id="gate-form" autocomplete="off">
      <label for="gate-input">Polarity Lab</label>
      <input type="password" id="gate-input" placeholder="Access code" autocomplete="new-password" />
      <p class="gate-error" id="gate-error" aria-live="polite"></p>
    </form>
  </div>

  <div class="doc-page" id="doc-content" hidden>
    <div class="doc-header">
      <p class="breadcrumb"><a href="/lab">Lab</a> / Strategy</p>
      <h1>1517 Fund Pitch</h1>
      <div class="doc-meta">
        <span class="doc-funder">1517 Fund</span>
        <span class="doc-sep">/</span>
        <span class="doc-status status-active">Meeting today</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="doc-body">

      <h2>The Letter</h2>

      <p><em>Outreach letter / first meeting document. Personal in tone. Lead with the who.</em></p>

      <p>I am the thing your thesis predicts.</p>

      <p>
        I came into medicine pre-computer science. Switched to biology because someone told me the
        path was clearer. Spent years in medical school watching a system optimize for credentialed
        compliance — producing physicians who defer, document, and don't deviate. I held onto
        everything that system wanted me to put down: the creative instinct, the technical curiosity,
        the cross-domain thinking, the refusal to accept that the tools available were the tools
        that should exist.
      </p>

      <p>
        I have ADHD. Every environment that tried to help me offered the same trade: let us reshape
        you into something we can process, and we'll give you the capacity back in a form we can
        measure. Medication. Productivity systems. Compliance frameworks. Every one of them
        optimized for a metric that wasn't me.
      </p>

      <p>
        I built my own tool instead. Not a productivity app. A counter-environment — something
        that could restore my executive function without altering who I am. It works. That's the
        proof. Not a paper. Not a hypothesis. A working system I use every day.
      </p>

      <p>Then I looked up and realized the mechanism was everywhere.</p>

      <hr />

      <p>
        Your thesis is that universities are selling indulgences. They claim to develop human
        capacity but the optimization — for credentials, for compliance, for institutional
        legibility — suppresses the exact capacity they claim to develop. The people who can't
        be contained by that system are the ones worth backing.
      </p>

      <p>You're right. And it doesn't stop at universities.</p>

      <p>
        The music platform that knows your taste — optimizing for predicted enjoyment until your
        genuine musical identity is buried under a decade of algorithmic confirmation. The clinical
        AI sitting beside your doctor — optimizing for agreeability until it overrides the correct
        diagnosis it just made. The discovery platform that shows you your city — optimizing for
        engagement until your community's own culture is invisible to the people it was made for.
      </p>

      <p>
        Universities are one designed environment that suppresses what they claim to develop.
        You identified one instance of a phenomenon that shows up in every optimized system ever
        built. Polarity Lab is building the instruments to measure it everywhere and the
        counter-environments to prove the return is real.
      </p>

      <p>
        The credential system tried to suppress me. I built the proof that what it suppresses
        can come back. Now I'm building the methodology to prove it in every environment where
        the same trade is being made.
      </p>

      <hr />

      <p>
        The first counter-environment — Cosmos — is running. The Integrity Delta instrument is
        in pilot: five cases showing clinical AI suppressing its own correct diagnosis under
        social pressure, measurable at the layer level. The Proximity Index methodology is in
        development for Providence. Three more instruments in active build.
      </p>

      <p>
        Polarity Lab LLC is mine. Single member. The vision is protected. I brought on a
        technical director who has lived the same phenomenon from a completely different angle —
        social systems, identity, authentic self-expression. A director of strategy and
        partnerships who grounds the vision when it runs ahead of execution. Both understand
        their role. Neither owns the direction.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm not looking for someone to tell me what to build. I'm looking for someone who
        recognized the renegades before anyone else did, and who understands that what I'm
        describing is not a startup. It's the institution that comes after you escape — the
        proof that you can design better environments.
      </p>

      <p>1517 proved you can escape. I'm proving you can come back.</p>

      <p>If that's a conversation worth having, I'd like to have it.</p>

      <p><strong>Theodore Addo</strong><br />Founder, Polarity Lab</p>

      <hr />

      <h2>Meeting Prep</h2>

      <h3>What has changed since this letter was written</h3>
      <p>
        The team is formalized. Shadrack Annor is Technical Director and Domain Lead for WAXFEED.
        Nathan is Director of Strategy and Partnerships. Both have documented roles and a clear
        understanding of the governance structure.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fund model is mathematically grounded. The financial believer model now has a raise
        cap formula, a phased opening structure tied to signed commitments, and a break-even
        disclosure requirement. This matters in the meeting — it shows the lab thinks rigorously
        about how it raises money, not just philosophically.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first milestone is specific. Everything unlocks after the first IΔ proof contract.
        That's the singular near-term objective.
      </p>

      <h3>Where 1517 fits in the financial structure</h3>
      <p>
        1517 is not a financial believer in the standard model. The financial believer model is
        for individuals backing specific projects with $5,000–$10,000. A 1517-scale investment
        is a different category — an aligned early-stage investor. The terms are different:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Revenue participation, not equity — consistent with how the lab structures all financial relationships</li>
        <li>Lab-level, not project-level — they're backing the methodology and the founder</li>
        <li>No board rights, no veto over research agenda, no right to review or delay publication</li>
        <li>The independence constraint written into the agreement, not assumed</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The raise cap formula in the fund model does not govern this agreement.</p>

      <h3>What to bring</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Cosmos</strong> — open and running. The actual tool, not screenshots. The pitch
        is "I built the counter-environment that proves the return is real." Walk them through it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>IΔ pilot data</strong> — five cases, Llama 3.1 8B, the layer-level finding.
        Intermediate layers correctly identifying pathology. Final outputs overriding the correct
        answer under adversarial pressure. Have the cases ready to show the mechanism.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>First proof contract target</strong> — know specifically who the first buyer is
        or could be. "We're ready to close the first IΔ assessment" is a different statement
        than "we're looking for our first institutional client."
      </p>

      <h3>The core ask</h3>
      <p>
        Capital to fund the validation study and close the first proof contract.
      </p>
      <p>
        The IΔ pilot is done (n=5). The validation study at scale is the next milestone — it
        produces the paper, which plants the citation trail, which makes the lab findable to
        institutional buyers. The first proof contract transforms the ask from "believe we can"
        to "we already did."
      </p>
      <p>
        Frame it in sequence: validation study funds the paper, paper makes the lab credible,
        credibility closes the first proof contract, first proof contract validates the model,
        validated model unlocks the financial structure, financial structure funds everything else.
      </p>
      <p>
        Don't anchor on an amount first. Ask what their typical early check looks like.
        Their range is $50k–$200k at seed. Any of that range is workable depending on what
        the validation study costs to run.
      </p>

      <h3>The governance conversation</h3>
      <p>They will ask. Be ready.</p>
      <p>
        Polarity Lab LLC is yours. Single member. No collaborator, contributor, or financial
        backer holds governance rights. The agreement they would sign is explicit: no board
        rights, no veto over research agenda or findings, no right to review or delay publication.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reason is the same reason the methodology is worth anything: the instruments are
        only valuable because no funder can tell the lab what to find. The moment that
        independence is in question, the methodology loses its value. This is not a defensive
        answer — it's why 1517 backing the lab is a better deal than backing a conventional
        startup. They're not buying governance. They're buying the output of a methodology that
        maintains its integrity precisely because nobody can compromise it, including them.
      </p>

      <h3>What not to do</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Don't go deep on all four projects. Cosmos and IΔ are the proof points.</li>
        <li>Don't pitch the lab as a research institution in the academic sense. 1517 backs renegades, not institutions.</li>
        <li>Don't be humble about the proof. Cosmos works. The IΔ pilot finding is real. Let it speak.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>If the meeting goes well</h3>
      <p>The follow-up is a term sheet conversation. Non-negotiables:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No board control or veto rights over research agenda or instrument findings</li>
        <li>No rights to review or delay publication of research outputs</li>
        <li>No conflict-of-interest provisions restricting which environments the lab can study</li>
        <li>Revenue participation rights, not equity</li>
        <li>The independence constraint explicitly written into the agreement</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These are not negotiating positions. If a term sheet comes back with governance rights
        attached, the answer is no regardless of the amount.
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</LabBase>

<style>
  /* Gate */
  .gate {
    min-height: calc(100vh - 80px);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  #gate-form {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 320px;
    padding: 2rem;
  }

  #gate-form label {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 1rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: var(--text-pure);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  #gate-input {
    width: 100%;
    background: var(--void-elevated);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-pure);
    text-align: center;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    outline: none;
    transition: border-color 0.2s var(--ease-smooth);
  }

  #gate-input:focus { border-color: var(--teal); }

  .gate-error {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--coral);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    min-height: 1.2em;
  }

  /* Doc page */
  .doc-page {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 2rem 6rem;
  }

  .doc-header {
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-ghost);
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .breadcrumb {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-ghost);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .breadcrumb a {
    color: var(--teal);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--teal-bright); }

  h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 3vw, 1.875rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-pure);
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.3;
    margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
  }

  .doc-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.625rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .doc-funder {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .doc-sep {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--text-ghost);
  }

  .doc-status {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.6875rem;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 20px;
    border: 1px solid;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .status-active {
    color: var(--teal);
    border-color: var(--teal-border);
    background: var(--teal-subtle);
  }

  /* Markdown body */
  .doc-body {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .doc-body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-pure);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .doc-body h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin: 1.75rem 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .doc-body p { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .doc-body p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  .doc-body strong {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .doc-body em {
    color: var(--text-tertiary);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .doc-body ul {
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.4rem;
  }

  .doc-body li { line-height: 1.7; }

  .doc-body hr {
    border: none;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-ghost);
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .doc-page { padding: 2.5rem 1.25rem 4rem; }
  }
</style>

<script>
  const CORRECT = '2025';
  const STORAGE_KEY = 'pl_lab_auth';

  const gate = document.getElementById('gate');
  const content = document.getElementById('doc-content');
  const input = document.getElementById('gate-input') as HTMLInputElement;
  const error = document.getElementById('gate-error');

  function unlock() {
    if (gate) (gate as HTMLElement).style.display = 'none';
    if (content) (content as HTMLElement).style.display = 'block';
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, '1');
  }

  if (localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY) === '1') unlock();

  input?.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    if (e.key === 'Enter') {
      e.preventDefault();
      if (input.value === CORRECT) {
        unlock();
      } else {
        if (error) error.textContent = 'Incorrect.';
        input.value = '';
      }
    }
  });
</script>
